# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] The **1884 Baltimore Monumentals** finished with a 58–47 record in the Union Association, finishing in fourth place.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] This was the only season this version of the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1884 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 14th season of the franchise.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-boston-reds-season] The **1884 Boston Reds** finished with a 58–51 record in the Union Association, finishing in fifth place (fourth among teams that played a full schedule).
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-boston-reds-season] This was the only season the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **1884 Brooklyn Atlantics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] It was the first season in the American Association for the team, and they finished the year in ninth place.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn baseball team had played as the **Brooklyn Grays** in the Interstate Association in 1883, where they won the championship.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] In 1884, Charles Byrne moved the team into the American Association, renaming them the Atlantics in tribute to the old National Association Brooklyn Atlantics team.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1884 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 64–47 record, good for third place in the National League.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season] The **1884 Toledo Blue Stockings** finished with a 45–58 record, eighth place in the American Association.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season] This was the only season the team was in a major league.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season] The team was noteworthy for catcher Fleet Walker and outfielder Weldy Walker, two brothers who are credited as being the first and second African Americans to play Major League Baseball before the color barrier prevented blacks from playing in the majors again until 1947.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] The **1884 Chicago Browns/Pittsburgh Stogies** finished with a 41–50 record (34–39 while in Chicago, 7–11 while in Allegheny City) in the Union Association, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] The team moved from Chicago to Allegheny City (today a part of Pittsburgh's North Shore) after their game of August 22.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] The team folded completely after their game of September 18, which was about a month before the 1884 season was scheduled to be over.
[src:1884-toledo-blue-stockings-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] With the Wilmington Quicksteps also having folded on September 21, and with about a dozen games remaining to be played, for the final games of the season the two defunct teams were replaced by teams from Milwaukee and St.
